1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 {In this line,
which I used to play very frequently in blitz, though never in a tournament
game, White tries to build a strong pawn centre. Black has to know what he is
doing since otherwise he risks coming under a strong attack.} O-O (6... d5 {
Leads to a different kind of position.}) (6... Nc6 7. e4 d6 {would be the
thematic continuation for Black.}) 7. e4 d6 (7... Nxe4 $2 {does not work.} 8.
fxe4 Qh4+ 9. Kd2 Qxe4 10. Nf3 $18 {Black has no compensation for the piece
since he is too far behind in development.}) 8. Bd3 {The most natural and best
move. Where should the g1-knight be developed? The knight will most often go
to e2. Long-term, the knight would great on e3, however, White cannot often
achieve this.} (8. Bg5 {This is premature at this point, but it remains an
important idea.}) 8... e5 9. d5 (9. Ne2 Nc6 10. d5 {Where should Black's
knight go? Is 10...Na5 good?} Na5 $2 {For this move to be good, the following
requirement must be met: 1) It's a theoretical move 2) If Black can attack and
win the c4-pawn Here, ...Na5 is a mistake. For example} 11. Ng3 b6 12. Nf1 Ba6
13. Ne3 {White was able to comfortably protect c4 and as a consequence the
a5-knight and a6-bishop are badly placed. Let me show you a strong and elegant
idea for White:} Ne8 14. O-O Rb8 15. g3 Qc7 16. a4 Qd7 17. Ra2 $1 {This is it
- the rook is transferred to the kingside via the 2nd rank. Now White is ready
to attack on the kingside.} f6 18. f4 Qc7 19. f5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ya2g2,Yg3g4,
Yg4g5] Such a position can be assessed as strategically winning for White.})
9... Nbd7 {Now Black cannot even dream about effectively attacking c4.} 10. Ne2
Ne8 11. h4 $1 {Why this move? White wants to expand with g4 on the kingside,
but he does not like to allow ...Qh4+. The move g4 will be played on the next
move, gaining space and preventing any possible counterplay with ...f5.} Nb6
12. g4 Qd7 {Creating the positional threat of ...Qa4. Exchanging queens would
be in Black's favour - even if he is still worse in the endgame - since
without queens, White's attack on the kingside is less dangerous.} 13. a4 $1 {
White's bishop on d3 may look bad, but we must evaluate the position as a
whole! This bishop fulfills the task of stabilising the centre, freeing the
rest of White's pieces to do the job!} Qe7 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. a5 Nc8 16. Ra2 Rb8
17. Nf5 Qd8 18. g5 b5 {Black correctly tries to create counterplay but White's
attack on the kingside will be too strong.} 19. cxb5 Bxb5 20. c4 Bd7 21. h5 {
It is possible to carry out an attack on the flank because the centre is
closed.} Bxf5 22. exf5 f6 23. h6 $1 {The move h6 is neither good or bad - it's
forced!} fxg5 24. hxg7 Rf7 25. f6 Nxf6 26. Bxg5 Rxg7 27. Bxh7+ $1 $18 {[%emt 0:
00:09] White won in a few moves in this blitz game.} Rxh7 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 28.
Rxh7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Kxh7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 29. Qd3+ {[%emt 0:00:03]} e4 {
[%emt 0:00:08]} 30. fxe4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Qe7 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 31. e5+ {
[%emt 0:00:02]} Kg8 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 32. Bxf6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} 1-0

