1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 c5 7. d5 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 d6 9. e3 e5 10. Nd2 {White is doing quite well, however, I would prefer
to have the dark-squared bishop on c1 instead of h4. Against the bishop on h4,
Black will at some point play ...g5.} Qe7 (10... g5 $5 11. Bg3 Bf5) 11. Bd3
Nbd7 $2 {After this, Black ends up in a very passive position.} 12. Qe2 Re8 13.
f3 $1 {A cunning move. White will eventually play e4 but for now it's useful
to keep f4 under control.} (13. e4 Nf8 14. f3 Ng6 $132) 13... b6 14. a4 Ba6 $2
15. e4 $1 {This is the right moment to play e4 since White is in time to
prevent ...Nf8-g6-f4.} Nf8 ({If} 15... g5 16. Bf2 Nh5 17. g3 Rab8 18. Nf1 $18 {
, followed by Ne3, exploiting the weak f5-square.}) 16. Bf2 $1 Ng6 17. g3 $1
$16 {After preventing Black's counterplay, White can quietly strengthen his
position.} Reb8 18. Nf1 $1 Bc8 19. Ne3 Nf8 20. h4 g6 $2 {This needlessly
creates a target.} 21. g4 Bd7 22. Qd2 a6 23. Nf1 $1 {The knight was good on e3
but now the situation has changed: White needs the e3-square for his bishop to
target the h6-pawn.} Kg7 24. Ng3 Ng8 25. O-O $3 Qe8 26. Be3 $3 {The pawn on a4
is no longer important - White will break through on the kingside.} Bxa4 (26...
Rb7 27. g5 h5 28. f4 exf4 29. Bxf4 Qe7 30. Rae1 Bxa4 31. e5 $18) 27. f4 $1 Bd7
(27... exf4 28. Bxf4 Rd8 29. h5 (29. Rae1 $18 {[%cal Ye4e5]}) 29... g5 30. Nf5+
$18) 28. f5 f6 29. g5 $1 {The final assault starts - White is winning.} fxg5
30. hxg5 hxg5 31. Bxg5 Nh7 32. f6+ $1 Ngxf6 33. Bxf6+ Nxf6 34. Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 35.
Rf1+ Bf5 (35... Kg7 36. Qg5 $18) 36. exf5 $18 Ke7 37. fxg6 Kd8 38. Rf7 Qh8 1-0

