1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8.
bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 h6 (11... Ng6 $1 {is best.}) 12. Qf3 Ng6
13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. Qxf5 $16 {There exists a common misconception: "In a closed
position, knights are stronger than bishops." This may be right for some cases,
but for example in the current position, White has some advantage. White
controls more space and since Black cannot afford to open the position to get
counterplay - this would favour the pair of bishops - the second player has no
counterplay.} Nh7 15. Rb1 {Since ...b6 would give White the option to play
a4-a5, Black has to defend b7 with a piece.} Qe7 16. g3 Rac8 17. h4 Rc7 18. Rb2
Qd7 19. Kg2 Qxf5 20. exf5 Nh8 21. Be2 $1 f6 ({White played Be2 with the
intention to meet} 21... Nf6 {with} 22. g4 {Black suffers from a lack of space.
For example} Nd7 23. g5 f6 24. g6 $18) 22. Bh5 Rd8 23. Re1 Nf7 24. Kf3 Rdd7 (
24... e4+ 25. Rxe4 Ne5+ 26. Ke2 $18) 25. Ke4 $16 {White later won the game by
executing the lever f4 at the right moment. He was even able to put a rook on
e6! I encourage you to study the rest of the game!} Nf8 26. Be3 Nh7 27. Reb1
Nd8 28. Rb3 Rc8 29. Ra3 a6 30. Rab3 Rcc7 31. Rb6 Nf7 32. g4 Kf8 33. Bg6 Kg8 34.
f4 Nf8 35. Bh5 Nh7 36. Bd2 Kf8 37. Rg1 exf4 38. Bxf7 Kxf7 39. Bxf4 Ke7 40. Re1
Nf8 41. Kd3+ Kd8 42. Re6 Nxe6 43. fxe6 Re7 44. h5 1-0

