1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. a3 $6
{A dubious move. Compared to the game Carlsen-Hossain, Black will be a healthy
tempo up.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 Ne4 10. Qc2 f5 11. Nd2 Qh4 12. f3 ({After} 12. Nxe4 $2
fxe4 $17 {White's position is cut in two, giving Black good attacking chances
on the kingside.}) 12... Nxd2 13. Bxd2 Nc6 14. Be1 Qf6 15. Rd1 d6 16. Bf2 e5
$17 {The opening has been a success for Black. He has lots of space and
White's bishops are shut in.} 17. d5 Na5 18. Rc1 ({After} 18. e4 f4 {[%cal
Yg7g5,Yg5g4] Black will continue by pushing his g-pawn.}) 18... Rae8 19. f4 Ba6
20. Qa2 exf4 21. exf4 Re4 $5 {A nice positional exchange sacrifice.} 22. Rfe1
Rxe1+ 23. Bxe1 Re8 24. Bd2 g6 25. Re1 Re7 26. g3 Kf8 27. Rxe7 Qxe7 {Since c4
is permanently weak, Black has good winning chances. Indeed, he came up with a
remarkable winning plan, involving the transfer of his king to a5!} 28. Kf2 (
28. Kg2 Bxc4 $1 $19) 28... Ke8 29. Be3 Kd8 30. Bd2 Kc7 31. Be3 Qe8 32. a4 (32.
Bd2 Qa4 $19) 32... Bc8 33. Bd2 Bd7 34. Bc2 Qf8 35. Bd3 Qh6 36. h4 Qf8 37. Be3
Qe8 38. Bc2 h5 39. Bd2 Nb7 40. Be3 Na5 41. Bd2 Kb7 42. Be3 Ka6 43. Bd2 Nb7 44.
Be3 Ka5 45. Bd2 Nd8 $1 {Since White cannot do anything it's a good idea to
improve the knight.} (45... a6 $4 {Of course we do not play this, but it
introduces an amusing helpmate:} 46. Qb3 Nd8 47. Qb4+ cxb4 48. cxb4#) 46. Be3
Nf7 47. Bd2 Nh6 48. Qa1 Ng4+ 49. Kf3 Nf6 50. Qb1 Bxa4 {Finally Black takes the
pawn. Now his task is to unpin the bishop.} 51. Qa2 a6 52. Qa3 b5 $19 53. cxb5
axb5 54. c4+ Kb6 55. cxb5 Bxb5 56. Bd3 Bxd3 57. Qxd3 Qe4+ 58. Qxe4 Nxe4 0-1

