1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e4
e5 9. d5 Ne7 $1 {This is the right square for the knight. We already discussed
why 9...Na5 would have been a mistake.} 10. g3 {Black wants to create
counterplay by preparing ...f5 or ...g5.} h6 11. Nh4 g5 12. Ng2 {White
reroutes the knight to e3 - this was the idea behind 10.g3.} Qa5 {Black
prepares castling queenside in the most active way.} 13. Qb3 Bh3 14. O-O O-O-O
15. Rb1 Qc7 16. f3 Kb8 17. Rf2 Rhg8 18. Ne3 Bc8 {It turns out that White
doesn't have a constructive plan! Black. on the other hand, will prepare a
pawn break on the kingside.} 19. Kf1 Rdf8 20. Ke1 Ne8 21. Nf5 {White
physically prevents ...f5. But the resulting structure renders his bishps
powerless.} Nxf5 22. exf5 f6 ({I would have preferred to use this square with
the knight. But Huebner chose a different plan.} 22... Nf6 $1 $17) 23. g4 ({
White cannot open the position:} 23. f4 exf4 24. gxf4 g4 $19) 23... Rh8 24. Be3
h5 25. Bf1 Rf7 26. h3 Qd7 27. Kd2 Nc7 28. a4 Re7 29. Re1 Na8 30. a5 Qd8 31. Qa3
Rhh7 32. Rb1 b6 $3 {An amazing move!! Black correctly evaluates that he can
open the b-file to his advantage. White's bishops are shut in on the kingside,
and Black can play on both flanks.} 33. Bd3 Rb7 34. axb6 Nxb6 35. Ra1 Qh8 36.
Kc2 hxg4 37. hxg4 Bd7 38. Qa2 Rh2 39. Kd2 Rxf2+ 40. Bxf2 Qh2 41. Ke2 Na4 42.
Qd2 Be8 43. Rb1 Rxb1 44. Bxb1 Qf4 45. Bd3 Qxd2+ 46. Kxd2 Nb6 47. Kc1 Ba4 48.
Bc2 Bd7 49. Bd3 Kc7 50. Kb2 Bc8 51. Kb3 Ba6 52. Be3 Nxd5 0-1

