1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bd2 Re8 8.
Nge2 {In this structure, White's main plans are: 1) Play f3 and e4 2) Play f3
and g4 3) Play a3 and b4} Bd6 9. Rc1 {White threatens to exchange Black's
bishop with Nb5.} a6 {Black plays ...a6 instead of ...c6 because he wants to
keep the option to play ...c5 in one move. The move ...c5 is an important
method to fight against the plan with f3-e4.} (9... c6 10. O-O Nbd7 11. f3 c5 {
is also playable, however, Black would have liked to reach this position with
the extra move ...a6.}) 10. Qb3 {White puts pressure on d5 to discourage ...c5.
} (10. O-O Nbd7 11. f3 c5) 10... c6 11. f3 Nbd7 12. O-O $2 {This is already a
mistake! These positions are very complicated and the assessment depends on
nuances. Even though the computer assesses these positions quite favourably
for Black, players who like complex positions go for them!} (12. e4 $5 c5 13.
Nxd5 $13) 12... b5 $17 {White does not manage to play e4 under favourable
circumstances.} 13. Bb1 (13. e4 c5 $1 $17) (13. Qd1 c5 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bb1 g6
(15... b4) (15... Bb7 $15)) 13... Nb6 $2 ({Due to concrete reasons the move} 
13... a5 $1 $17 {was best. For example} 14. Rfe1 (14. e4 $2 b4 15. Na4 dxe4 16.
Rxc6 exf3 $19) 14... Nb6 15. e4 b4 16. e5 bxc3 17. Bxc3 Bc7 18. exf6 Qxf6 $17)
14. e4 $1 $132 b4 $2 15. Nd1 dxe4 (15... Nc4 16. Bg5 $1) 16. fxe4 Nxe4 {
Black must destroy White's pawn centre.} ({Defending passively is insufficient.
} 16... Be6 $2 17. Qd3 g6 18. Bg5 (18. e5 $18) 18... Nbd7 19. Nf4 $18 (19. Ne3
$18)) 17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Bg5 $1 $14 {The tables have turned -
White has the initiative.} Qg8 20. Rxc6 Qxf7 21. Rxf7 Rxe2 $4 (21... Be6 $11)
22. Rxd6 Be6 23. Re7 Re1+ 24. Kf2 Rxd1 25. Rdxe6 $18 Rf8+ 26. Ke2 Rg1 27. Rf7
Rxg2+ 28. Kf3 Rxf7+ 29. Kxg2 h6 30. Rxb6 hxg5 31. Rxb4 Rf6 32. Kg3 Kh7 33. d5
Rd6 34. Rd4 Kg6 35. Kg4 Kf6 36. Rd2 1-0

