1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Nge2 Re8 8.
Bd2 Bd6 9. Rc1 a6 10. O-O b6 11. f3 c5 (11... Bb7 {may be playable, though it
has to be carefully calculated. If White is allowed to build a strong pawn
centre, Black has to make sure that he can generate sufficient counterplay.
One mistake can change dramatically change the assessment!} 12. e4 Be7 $2 (
12... dxe4 13. fxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bc4 Bg6 16. Nf4 $13) 13. e5 Nfd7 14.
f4 $18) 12. Qe1 Nc6 13. Qh4 h6 14. Kh1 a5 $1 {A remarkable idea - Black
prepares to exchange the light-squared bishops to reduce White's attacking
potential.} 15. Rfd1 $6 ({Better was} 15. Nb5 Be7 16. Qf2 a4 $15 {Even if the
position is better for Black according to the computer, White's chances are
totally acceptable.}) 15... Ba6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 17. dxc5 bxc5 {Here Black is
somewhat better.} 18. Na4 Nb4 (18... c4 $1 $17) 19. Bxb4 $2 (19. Nxc5 $11)
19... cxb4 $17 20. Rd3 Qd7 21. b3 Rc6 22. Rcd1 Rc2 23. Qe1 Rxa2 24. Rc1 Qf5 25.
