{LESSON 2 > Botvinnik's strategy - White plays f3-e4 - White plays f3-g4 -
White takes dxc4 followed by c4 > Doubled pawns on d6 and d5 > Light-square
strategy > Various strategies}  *

[Event "39th Olympiad Women"]
[Site "Khanty-Mansiysk RUS"]
[Date "2010.09.21"]
[Round "1.5"]
[White "Tay Li Jin Jeslin"]
[Black "Pogonina, N."]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "E46"]
[WhiteElo "2119"]
[BlackElo "2491"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "110"]
[EventDate "2010.09.21"]
[EventType "team"]
[WhiteTeam "SIN"]
[BlackTeam "RUS2"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nge2 d5 6. a3 (6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bd2
c6 8. a3 Bd6 9. g3 Bf5 10. Bg2 Nbd7 11. O-O Re8) 6... Be7 7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 {
In my opinion, this is a very bad position for White! Strangely enough, it was
considered quite playable, and there exist many high-level games with this
variation. White can either play in the centre with f3-e4 or go for a minority
attack with b4. However, none of this is going to happen! Let's see Black's
ideas:} Nbd7 {Black has several other good moves, but I like 8...Nbd7 since
Black keeps the option of playing ...c5 in one go.} ({Another possible
continuation:} 8... c6 9. Bg2 a5 10. O-O Na6 11. f3 c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Nd4
Re8 14. Nce2 Nc7 15. b3 Ne6 16. Bb2 Bd7 17. Rc1 Bb6 18. Qd2 h5 $132) 9. Bg2 Nb6
10. O-O a5 {Now White can never start a minority attack, while f3 can always
be countered with ...c5.} 11. Nf4 (11. a4 Re8 $15) (11. b3 Re8 $15) 11... Re8
12. a4 (12. f3 c5 $1) 12... c6 13. b3 Bb4 {A high-level move - Black avoids
Ba3.} ({Black is also better after} 13... Bf5 14. Ba3 Bxa3 15. Rxa3 Nc8 16. Ra2
Nd6 $15) 14. Qc2 Qe7 15. Bb2 g6 $1 16. Nd3 Bf5 $15 {Black has an advantage.
The main reason is that his bishops are superior to their white counterparts.}
17. Qe2 Bd6 $1 18. Rfc1 Nbd7 $1 19. Nb1 h5 $1 $17 20. Ba3 (20. h4 {prevents ...
h4 but weakens g4.} Ng4 21. Ba3 Bxa3 22. Nxa3 g5 $1 {Black's attack is hard to
stop.} 23. hxg5 Qxg5 24. Nf4 h4 25. gxh4 Qxf4 $19 (25... Qxh4)) 20... Bxa3 $1
21. Nxa3 h4 $1 22. Nc2 Kg7 $1 {Black prepares ...Rh8.} 23. Nce1 hxg3 24. hxg3
Rh8 25. Nf3 Be4 26. Nc5 Nxc5 27. dxc5 Rh5 $1 $19 {Black has a very strong
attack.} 28. Qb2 Qd7 29. Ne5 Qe6 30. f3 Qxe5 31. Qxe5 Rxe5 32. fxe4 Nxe4 33.
Bxe4 Rxe4 34. Rc3 Rae8 35. Kf2 g5 36. Rd3 R8e6 37. Rg1 f5 38. Rh1 Rh6 39. Rxh6
Kxh6 40. Rd1 Rb4 41. Rh1+ Kg6 42. Rh8 Rxb3 43. Rg8+ Kh5 44. Ke2 Kg4 45. Rg7 Rc3
46. Rxb7 Kxg3 47. Rf7 Kg4 48. Ra7 Rxc5 49. Ra8 f4 50. exf4 Kxf4 51. Rf8+ Kg3
52. Rf3+ Kg4 53. Rf6 Rc4 54. Ke3 c5 55. Rc6 Kf5 0-1

[Event "AVRO"]
[Site "Holland"]
