1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2 b6 10. O-O {This is a typical structure in the Nimzo-Indian. I
recommend avoiding it as Black! White's main plan is to prepare for f3-e4 and
exploit his pawn majority in the centre. This worked to perfection in this
famous game!} Ba6 {It's logical to exchange the light-squared bishops to
reduce White's attacking potential.} 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Bb2 {White's bishop may
look very bad on b2, but later it will enter the game with great effect...} Qd7
13. a4 Rfe8 14. Qd3 c4 15. Qc2 Nb8 ({Let me demonstrate White's plan by
playing some random moves with Black:} 15... Rac8 16. Ng3 h6 17. Rae1 Nb8 18.
f3 Nc6 19. e4 Na5 20. e5 Nh7 21. f4 {Black should never allow such a scenario
- White has a winning advantage. For example} (21. Nf5 $5) 21... Nb3 22. f5
Qxa4 23. Qe2 $5 $18 (23. f6 $5) (23. Nh5 Nc5 $5)) 16. Rae1 Nc6 17. Ng3 Na5 18.
f3 Nb3 19. e4 Qxa4 {This was Capablanca's idea when playing ...c4. However
winning the a-pawn does not offer enough compensation for White's attack on
the kingside.} 20. e5 Nd7 21. Qf2 $1 (21. f4 Nbc5 $1 $132) 21... g6 22. f4 $18
{White conducted the attack in textbook fashion, and he managed to win in
great style.} f5 23. exf6 Nxf6 24. f5 Rxe1 25. Rxe1 Re8 26. Re6 Rxe6 27. fxe6
Kg7 28. Qf4 Qe8 29. Qe5 Qe7 30. Ba3 $3 Qxa3 31. Nh5+ gxh5 32. Qg5+ Kf8 33.
Qxf6+ Kg8 34. e7 Qc1+ 35. Kf2 Qc2+ 36. Kg3 Qd3+ 37. Kh4 Qe4+ 38. Kxh5 Qe2+ 39.
Kh4 Qe4+ 40. g4 Qe1+ 41. Kh5 1-0

