1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
e3 Bf5 {This is a major difference from the previous game - Black manages to
put his bishop on f5. White would have preferred to have played Bd3 instead of
f3.} (8... c5 9. Bd3 Re8 10. Ne2 b6 11. O-O) 9. Ne2 c5 10. g4 {A
super-interesting strategy - White uses the position of the bishop on f5 to
gain space.} (10. Ng3 {would be a logical alternative. For example} Bg6 11. Bd3
Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Nbd7 13. O-O Re8 {Now, White still needs some time to prepare e4.
} 14. e4 $2 dxe4 15. fxe4 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nc5 $1 $17) 10... Be6 ({After} 10...
Bg6 11. Nf4 {h4 is a threat.}) 11. Nf4 {After the retreat ...Be6 White is
better.} Nc6 {Black puts pressure on d4 in order to make e3-e4 more difficult.}
({After} 11... c4 12. Bg2 {White would have a free hand in the centre.}) 12.
Bd3 Rc8 (12... Qa5 13. Bd2) 13. h4 {White's king is quite safe in the centre -
he can afford to attack on the kingside.} Re8 14. O-O Nd7 (14... c4 15. Bb1 b5
16. g5 Nd7 17. e4 $18) 15. Ra2 $1 $16 {A typical manoeuvre that we have
already seen in lesson 1.} Nf8 16. h5 h6 17. Rg2 {White will eventually attack
with g4-g5.} a6 18. Nxe6 Nxe6 19. f4 b5 20. g5 hxg5 21. Qg4 b4 22. axb4 cxb4
23. fxg5 $18 {White's attack is irresistable.} Rc7 24. Qf5 Nf8 25. g6 f6 26. h6
bxc3 27. Qh5 Nb4 28. hxg7 Rxg7 29. Rh2 Nh7 30. Bf5 Na2 31. Rxa2 1-0

