1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
f3 c4 {Black's idea is to take away the d3-square from White's bishop. However,
releasing the pressure on White's centre is risky since he gets a free hand to
expand on the kingside.} 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. g4 $1 (10. Ng3) 10... h6 11. Bg2 Na5
12. O-O Nb3 13. Ra2 O-O 14. Ng3 {When I first studied this game (back in the
90s), I thought that Black's position was quite good! However, the opposite is
true. White has good attacking chances, and Kasparov was in his element!} Bd7
15. Qe1 Re8 16. e4 $1 {Kasparov does not mind sacrificing a pawn for the
initiative.} dxe4 17. fxe4 Nxg4 18. Bf4 Qh4 19. h3 Nf6 20. e5 $18 {White's
attack clearly outweighs Black's extra pawn.} Rad8 21. Qf2 Nh5 22. Bxh6 Re7 23.
Nf5 Qxf2+ 24. Rfxf2 Re6 25. Be3 Bc6 26. Bf1 f6 27. Bxc4 Bd5 28. Be2 fxe5 29.
Bxh5 exd4 30. Bg5 Rd7 31. Rae2 Be4 32. Nxd4 1-0

