1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8.
e3 b6 {We know this idea from the game Botvinnik-Capablanca. Black prepares to
exchange the light-squared bishops.} ({Let's suppose Black plays} 8... Nbd7 {
This logical-looking move is, in fact, a serious mistake. Black should take
measures to oppose White's plan, after which he gets into a difficult
situation. For example} 9. Bd3 Re8 10. Ne2 c5 11. O-O b6 12. Ng3 $16 (12. g4 $5
Bb7 13. Ng3 $16)) 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Ne2 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Re8 12. O-O c5 13. Ng3 Nc6 (
13... c4 $2 {is a serious mistake since White is no longer presented with any
difficulties to play e4.} 14. Qc2 Qe7 15. Bd2 (15. Bb2 Nc6 16. Rae1) 15... Nc6
16. e4 $16) (13... Nbd7 14. Bb2 (14. e4 $2 cxd4 15. cxd4 dxe4 16. fxe4 Nc5 $1
$17) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 $16) 14. Bb2 $14 Qd7 $2 {This is a serious positional
and tactical mistake!} (14... Na5 $2 {is ineffective - the knight has no
function on c4 while White carries out his plans.} 15. Rae1 Nc4 16. Bc1 cxd4
17. cxd4 Rc8 18. e4 dxe4 19. fxe4 Ne5 20. Qd2 Nc4 21. Qd1 $18 {White has a
winning positional advantage due to his poweful mobile pawn centre.}) (14...
Rc8 15. Rae1 Na5 $2 {- see the note to 14...Na5.} 16. e4 Nc4 17. Bc1 b5 18. e5
Nd7 19. f4 cxd4 20. cxd4 Qb6 21. Kh1 $18 (21. f5 $4 Ndxe5 $19)) (14... c4 {
This is the first line of the computer, however, it's not enough to equalise.
For example} 15. Qd2 (15. Qe2 h5 16. Qf2 $14 (16. e4 h4 17. Nf5 dxe4 18. fxe4
Rxe4 19. Qf3 $44)) 15... h5 16. Rae1 h4 17. Nf5 h3 18. e4 dxe4 19. Qg5 g6 20.
Nh6+ Kg7 21. fxe4 hxg2 22. Rf2 $18) 15. e4 $1 $16 {Firstly, White is able to
push e4 without further preparation.} dxe4 16. fxe4 Ne5 17. Qe2 Ng6 18. Rxf6 $1
$18 {Secondly, White is able to sacrifice the exchange on f6, leading to a
decisive attack - this is another drawback of 14...Qd7!} gxf6 19. Nh5 Re6 20.
d5 Rd6 21. c4 Ne5 22. Qf2 (22. h3 $5 Qe7 23. Rf1 Kh8 24. Rf5 $18) 22... Kf8 23.
Qg3 Re8 24. Qg7+ Ke7 25. Rf1 1-0

