1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6 (5... O-O 6. e3 d5 {
Let me formulate a general rule: if White has the pair of bishops, he should
take on d5 if Black plays ...d5.} 7. cxd5 $1 (7. Bd3 $6 {gives Black the
opportunity to play} dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 $132) 7... exd5 8. Bd3 {Here we get to
the familiar plans.}) 6. f3 (6. Bg5 $6 {The bishop does not belong on g5 in
these positions.}) 6... d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 (8. Bg5 $6 {For the time being,
this bishop is better placed on c1, where it solidly protects e3.} O-O 9. e3 h6
10. Bh4 Re8 $15) 8... O-O 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Ne2 c5 11. O-O Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 13.
Ng3 Nc6 14. Bb2 Qd7 $2 {Again, this mistake!} 15. e4 $1 $16 dxe4 16. fxe4 Ne5
17. Qa6 Nc6 18. Qd3 Ne5 19. Qe2 Ng6 20. Rxf6 $1 $18 gxf6 21. Rf1 (21. Nh5 $5
Re6 (21... Qe6 22. d5 $1 $18) 22. d5 Rd6 23. c4 $18) 21... Re6 22. d5 Re5 23.
c4 Rae8 24. Bxe5 Rxe5 25. Rxf6 Qa4 26. Qf1 b5 27. Rc6 Qxa3 28. cxb5 Qe3+ 29.
Kh1 Nf4 30. Rf6 Nd3 31. Rf3 1-0

