{I really like White's strategy in this game!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 Re8 9. Bd3 b6 10. Ne2 Bb7 $2 {
This is dubious. Black should have exchanged the bishops since White's
light-squared bishop is clearly stronger than his black counterpart.} 11. O-O
Nbd7 12. Ra2 $5 {White transfers his rook to the centre via the 2nd rank. The
basic goal is to prepare e4.} (12. Ng3 $5) (12. g4 $5) 12... Nf8 13. Ng3 c5 14.
Re2 cxd4 (14... c4 $2 {Taking the pressure off White's centre simplifies his
task.} 15. Bc2 Ng6 16. e4 b5 17. e5 Nd7 18. f4 Ngf8 19. f5 $18) 15. cxd4 Qd7
16. Bb2 Ne6 {Black manages to prevent e4 for now.} 17. Qd2 $1 {xf4} Rad8 18.
Nf5 Nf8 19. g4 $3 {White adjusts his strategy and starts expanding on the
kingside. Black's pieces are well-placed to fight against e4, but apart from
this, they do not have any prospects!} h6 20. Rg2 N6h7 21. h4 Qa4 22. Bc2 Qd7
23. Re1 Rc8 24. Bb1 Ng6 25. e4 $1 $18 {Finally, White got to play e4. Black's
pieces are now to passively placed to fight this.} Qd8 (25... dxe4 26. fxe4
Rcd8 27. d5 (27. Qf2 $5) 27... Ne5 28. Qf4 $18 (28. g5 $4 Nf3+ $19)) 26. g5
hxg5 27. hxg5 Nhf8 28. e5 Ne6 29. Rg4 Rc6 {Black would like to sacrifice the
exchange against a knight appearing on d6. White does not need to allow this
and instead prepares the decisive breakthrough.} 30. Rf1 Nef8 31. f4 Bc8 32.
Rg3 Bxf5 33. Bxf5 Nh4 34. Bd3 g6 35. Rh3 Nf5 36. Qh2 1-0

