1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Bd3 Bb7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O d5 (7...
Bxc3 8. bxc3 Ne4 9. Ne1 $1 {would lead to the game Carlsen-Hossain which we
studied in lesson 1.}) 8. a3 Bd6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 Nbd7 {Black's position
appears to be quite good. He has a great outpost on e4 for his knight, with
chances for counterplay on the kingside. However, his position has one
significant disadvantage: the passive b7-bishop. In this game, Topalov managed
to exploit this to perfection.} (10... a6 $142) 11. b5 $1 {White's basic plan
is to exchange the dark-squared bishops, leaving Black with a passive bishop
on b7.} Ne4 $2 ({Black should have played} 11... a6 {, stopping a4.} 12. Bb2
axb5 13. Nxb5 Be7 $11) (11... c5 $6 12. bxc6 Bxc6 13. a4 $16) 12. Bb2 Re8 13.
a4 Re6 14. Ne2 a5 (14... Qe7 15. Qb3) 15. Ba3 $1 {White has achieved his first
goal.} Rc8 16. Bxd6 cxd6 {This appears to be good since the doubled pawns
control a lot of squares. However, after exchanging several pieces, the
weakness of these pawns will become the decisive factor.} ({If instead} 16...
Nxd6 {then} 17. Rc1 {with a lasting advantage for White.} c6 18. bxc6 Bxc6 19.
Qb3 $16) 17. Rc1 Ndf6 18. h3 Re7 19. Qb3 h6 20. Rxc8 Qxc8 21. Rc1 Rc7 22. Rxc7
Qxc7 23. Qc2 $16 Qe7 (23... Qxc2 24. Bxc2 $16) 24. Qc1 g6 25. Nh2 Kg7 26. h4
Ne8 27. f3 N4f6 28. Nf1 h5 29. Nf4 {The knight is great on e4, not only
targeting d5 but also supporting an attack on the kingside.} Nd7 30. Qe1 Nf8
31. Qg3 Kh6 32. Nxh5 $5 {Topalov goes for an interesting piece sacrifice.
Objectively, it was better to keep manoeuvring, but 32.Nxh5 poses concrete
problems for Black.} (32. Kf2 Ng7 33. Nd2 $16) 32... gxh5 (32... Kxh5 $2 33.
Qf4 $1 g5 34. Ng3+ Kh6 35. Nf5+ $18) 33. Qg8 f5 34. Ng3 Ng7 35. Bxf5 Ng6 36.
Bxg6 Kxg6 37. Nxh5 Qxe3+ 38. Kh2 Qe7 $2 (38... Qxd4 $142 $11) 39. Nf4+ Kf6 40.
g4 $18 {Now Black is lost despite having an extra piece - he cannot coordinate
his forces.} (40. h5 $1 $18) 40... Qf7 41. Qd8+ Qe7 42. Qg8 Qf7 43. Qd8+ Qe7
44. Qxe7+ Kxe7 45. Kg3 {White's three connected passed pawns are much stronger
than Black' extra piece.} Ne6 46. Nxe6 Kxe6 47. f4 Bc8 48. f5+ Kf7 49. h5 Bd7
50. h6 Kg8 51. Kf4 Be8 52. Kg5 Kf7 53. h7 Kg7 54. h8=Q+ Kxh8 55. Kf6 Bxb5 56.
Ke7 Bd3 57. f6 Bg6 58. f7 Bxf7 59. Kxf7 1-0

