{A fantastic game by Ivanchuk! According to Topalov, he was inspired by this
game in his win over Sasikiran!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. e3
Bb4 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O d5 8. a3 Bd6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. b4 Nbd7 11. Bb2 Re8 $6 (
11... a6 $1 12. b5 (12. a4 $2 Bxb4) 12... axb5 13. Nxb5 Be7 $11) 12. Qc2 (12.
b5 $1) 12... a6 13. b5 (13. Rac1 b5 14. a4 c6 15. a5 Bxb4) 13... a5 (13... axb5
14. Nxb5 {and White manages to exchange the important dark-squared bishop on
d6.}) 14. a4 Ne4 (14... Qe7 15. Qb3 $16 Ne4 $2 16. Nxd5 $18) 15. Ba3 $16 Rc8
16. Rfc1 Ndf6 17. Qb2 Ng4 18. Nd1 {White is forced to defend against threats
on the kingside, but he is not worried. At the end of the day, Black will be
left with a passive bishop on b7, which cannot take part in the attack!} h6 19.
h3 Ngf6 20. Rc2 Qe7 21. Be2 Qe6 22. Rac1 Qe7 23. Bxd6 cxd6 {Again, this
structure is reached. Like in the previous example, White's strategy is to
simplify the position and play an ending with only minor pieces.} 24. Ne1 Rxc2
25. Rxc2 Rc8 26. Nd3 Rc4 27. Qc1 Qc7 28. Ne1 Rxc2 29. Qxc2 Qxc2 30. Nxc2 Ng5
31. f3 Kf8 32. Kf2 Ke7 33. Nc3 Ne6 34. Ne1 Kd8 35. Bd1 Ng8 36. Bb3 Ne7 {
Black's pieces are tied to the defence of his doubled pawns. White needs to
create a second weakness to make progress.} 37. Nd3 Kd7 38. h4 g5 39. hxg5 hxg5
40. g4 f6 41. Nc1 Ng7 42. N1e2 f5 (42... Ne6 43. Ng3 Ng7 44. f4 $1 Kc7 45. Nh5
Ne8 46. e4 $3 dxe4 47. Bf7 Kd7 48. f5 $1 $18 {Black is powerless against the
threat of Bxe8, followed by Nxf8-xe4.}) 43. gxf5 Ngxf5 44. Ng3 Ng7 45. Kg2 Ngf5
46. Nxf5 Nxf5 47. Kf2 Ke6 (47... Ne7 48. Kg3 $1 {It's time to calculate some
concrete variations!} (48. Bc2 {gives Black chances to defend.} Ke6 49. Kg3 Kf6
$14) 48... Nf5+ (48... Ke6 49. Kg4 Kf6 50. Kh5 Nf5 51. Bxd5 $18) 49. Kg4 Nxe3+
50. Kxg5 Ke6 51. f4 $18) 48. Ne4 Bc8 49. Nxg5+ {White managed to win a pawn
and to convert his advantage.} Kf6 50. f4 Bb7 51. Bd1 Nh6 52. Bf3 Kf5 53. Ke2
Ba8 54. Kd3 Ng8 55. Bg2 Nf6 56. Bh3+ Kg6 57. Bc8 Ne4 58. Ne6 Nf2+ 59. Kd2 Ne4+
60. Kc2 1-0

