{An even earlier high-level example of positions with doubled pawns on d5 and
d6!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. Bf4 Bb7 5. e3 Be7 6. h3 O-O 7. Nc3 d5 8.
cxd5 exd5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 $146 10. O-O a6 11. Ne5 Re8 12. Qf3 Bd6 13. Ng4 $1 $14
Ne4 $4 14. Bxd6 cxd6 $2 {Though this was not technically a Nimzo-Indian, we
arrives at this typical structure. Taking with the pawn on d6 creates
long-term weaknesses and similar to the previous examples, White was able to
exploit this.} (14... Nxd6 15. Qg3 $14) 15. Rfc1 $16 Qg5 16. Ne2 Rac8 17. Qf4
Qxf4 18. Nxf4 g6 19. f3 Nef6 20. Nxf6+ Nxf6 21. Kf2 Kf8 (21... h5 22. g4 $16 (
22. h4 $5 {In this position I would probably have played h4, with the
long-term idea of creating a passed pawn with g4 hxg4 fxg4, or to transfer the
king to f4.} Kg7 23. Ne2)) 22. g4 $1 (22. h4 {would have allowed to prevent g4
with} h5) 22... Ke7 23. h4 b5 {/\} 24. h5 Nd7 25. Rxc8 Rxc8 26. Rh1 Nf8 27.
hxg6 hxg6 28. Ke2 Kf6 29. Kd2 Kg7 30. Rc1 {This is maybe premature since it's
not guaranteed that the resulting endgame is winning. However, White managed
to convert his advantage since defending such a position is very tough.} Rxc1
31. Kxc1 Kf6 32. Kd2 b4 $2 (32... Kg5 $16) 33. Kc2 $18 a5 34. Bb5 $1 Ne6 35.
Nxe6 fxe6 36. Kb3 Kg5 37. Ka4 e5 38. Kxa5 exd4 39. exd4 Kf4 40. Bd7 Ke3 41. Kb6
Ba8 42. Ka7 Kxd4 43. f4 1-0

