1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. e3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 7. Bd3 Nc6 8.
O-O e5 9. Qc2 h6 {Black has a good version of the Huebner Variation he is
doing well.} 10. Bb2 $2 {The bishop is misplaced on b2 since Black will never
exchange the pawns in the centre.} O-O 11. Nd2 b6 12. Nb3 Bd7 13. Rae1 Re8 14.
Qb1 e4 $1 15. Bc2 Bf5 {Here, Black's strategy works perfectly - White's
bishops are completely blocked. With ...Bf5, Black overprotects e4. It is
essential to solidly control e4 so that White never manages to break with f3.}
({An example of what NOT to do with Black:} 15... Qc7 16. f3 exf3 17. gxf3 Re7
18. e4 {Now White is back in the game.}) 16. f3 Bh7 17. Nd2 Qe7 18. f4 Bf5 $17
19. Bd1 Na5 20. h3 h5 $1 {Black follows the same strategy as in the famous
game Johner-Nimzowitsch.} 21. Kh2 g6 22. Rg1 Kg7 $19 {Black will put his rooks
on the h- and g-files and eventually prepare the decisive breakthrough ...g5.}
(22... Ng4+ {was winning right away according to the computer.}) 23. Rh1 (23.
g4 hxg4 24. hxg4 Rh8+ 25. Kg3 Nxg4 26. Bxg4 Qh4+ $19) 23... Qe6 24. Be2 Rh8 25.
Kg1 Rag8 26. Kf2 Kf8 27. Ref1 g5 28. Ke1 h4 29. fxg5 Rxg5 30. Rf2 Nh5 31. Bxh5
Rhxh5 32. Rhf1 Rg3 33. d5 Rxe3+ 34. Re2 Rxe2+ 35. Kxe2 Qg6 0-1

