1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 5. Nge2 Ne4 6. Bd2 Nxd2 7. Qxd2 O-O 8.
a3 Be7 9. Nf4 c6 10. Bd3 d5 11. Qc2 h6 12. h4 $1 {White has played the opening
quite strongly, and he achieved some advantage. h4 is ambitious and strong!}
Bd6 13. Nfe2 (13. Nce2 $5) 13... Ba6 14. cxd5 (14. g4 $1 {was the consistend
continuation. For example} Bxc4 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. g5 h5 17. f4 $16) 14... Bxd3
15. Qxd3 cxd5 16. Rc1 Nd7 17. g3 $6 {White loses the thread of the game and
slowly drifts into a worse position.} ({Again, White should have continued with
} 17. g4 $1 {Black has problems with his knight on d7. After g4, it cannot go
to f6.} f5 {This could be considered to gain counterplay, but after this
Black's king will be weak.} (17... g6 {with the idea to close the position,
can be met with} 18. g5 hxg5 19. hxg5 Qxg5 20. f4 Qe7 21. e4 Kg7 22. e5 $16) (
17... Nf6 18. g5 $40) (17... a6 18. g5 h5 19. e4 $1 $16) 18. Nb5 Bb8 (18... Nf6
19. g5 hxg5 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. hxg5 Ne4 22. g6 Rac8 23. Rc2 $16) 19. gxf5 Rxf5
20. Qc2 a6 21. Qc6 axb5 22. Qxa8 $18) 17... a6 18. a4 $6 ({The game is about
equal after} 18. O-O {for example} b5 19. a4 bxa4 (19... b4 20. Nb1 Nb6 21. b3
Qd7 22. Nd2 $14) 20. Nxa4 Qa5 $11) 18... Nf6 19. h5 $6 {After the 3rd dubious
move in a row, Black is clearly better. White needlessly created weaknesses
with a4 and h5.} (19. O-O Qd7 $15) 19... Qd7 20. Kf1 Rfe8 (20... Qb7 $15) 21.
Kg2 e5 22. dxe5 Rxe5 23. Rh4 (23. Nd4 $5) 23... Qb7 24. Kg1 Rae8 25. Nf4 Bc5
26. Qd1 $6 d4 $1 $17 27. exd4 Bxd4 28. Ng2 Bc5 29. b4 Be7 30. Ne3 Rd8 31. Qb3
$2 Nxh5 $19 (31... Rxe3 $1 32. fxe3 Qf3 $19) 32. Rh3 Qf3 33. Re1 Bg5 34. Ncd1
Bxe3 35. Nxe3 Rd2 36. Rf1 Re2 0-1

