[EventType "team (rapid)"]
[EventRounds "11"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Nf3 O-O 6. g3 (6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 {
is another popular continuation, when} Nc6 8. g3 e5 $5 {is an interesting way
to continue with Black.} ({If we prepare ...e5 with} 8... Qe7 9. Bg2 e5 10. d5
{the e7-square is no longer available for our knight.}) (8... a5 9. b3 {
could be inserted, but now Black must choose a plan.}) 9. dxe5 (9. d5 {is met
with} Ne7 {when Black can prepare ...f5 or attack White's centre with ...b5.})
9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Qxe5 Re8 12. Qc3 Ne4 $44 {Black has good
compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 6... b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O {With her
move order, White hopes to provoke the exchange on c3, saving a tempo on
playing a3.} Nbd7 {This is possible - Black's bishop cannot be trapped.} 9. Bd2
(9. Nd1 {needs to be considered.} d5 10. c5 ({After} 10. cxd5 exd5 $11 {
it is not clear why the knight went to d1.}) 10... bxc5 11. a3 Ba5 12. dxc5 c6
13. b4 Bc7 {The computer assesses this as better for White, but in my opinion
Black's position is entirely playable.}) (9. a3 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 c5 $5) 9... a5 $5
{There are two main ideas for Black: 1) Playing ...c5 2) Playing ...a5, take
on c3, and put the bishop on e4} (9... c5 $5 {- Plan Nr. 1. If White takes on
c5} 10. dxc5 {Black's main options are taking with the b-pawn or with the
knight.} Nxc5 $132 {[%cal Ya8c8]} (10... bxc5)) (9... Bxc3 {This is premature
- I just want to show Black's ideas:} 10. Bxc3 Be4 $1 ({If} 10... Ne4 {the
knight is not well-placed on e4 since it is pinned. For example} 11. Be1 (11.
Ne1 f5 12. b3 $14) 11... f5 12. d5 $5 $36) 11. Qc1 a5 $1 (11... h6 {This tends
to be useful. However, here, it is slightly inaccurate since it allows} 12. b4
$1)) 10. b3 (10. a3 $6 {After ...a5, this is a mistake.} Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Be4 12.
Qc1 a4 $15 {Black fixes the queenside, limiting White's options.} (12... h6 $5
13. b4 (13. b3 c6 {[%cal Yd6d5,Yb6b5]}) 13... axb4 14. axb4 {Another
interesting idea for Black is} b5 $5 15. cxb5 Nb6 16. Ra5 Qd7 $44) 13. Nd2 ({or
} 13. Rd1 h6) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {Black has various ideas to attack White's
centre:} c5 $5 (14... d5 $5) (14... b5 $5 15. cxb5 Qb8 16. e4 Qxb5) 15. e4 cxd4
16. Bxd4 Nc5 $15) 10... Qe7 11. a3 ({After} 11. Rfe1 {Black can take control
of the centre with} Bxc3 12. Bxc3 Be4 $11) 11... Bxc3 12. Bxc3 c5 ({Black
could also insert} 12... Be4 13. Qb2 {and only the play} c5 {, with good
counterplay.} 14. dxc5 bxc5 {Black is fine in this position. White has the
pair of bishops, but Black has active pieces.}) 13. Rad1 (13. dxc5 Nxc5 $5 (
13... bxc5 $5) 14. Ng5 e5 $132) 13... Rfc8 $2 {A mistake; Black should have
played} (13... Be4 $1 14. Qb2 Rfc8 15. dxc5 bxc5 $36) 14. Qb2 $2 ({White the
very promising and thematic sacrifice} 14. d5 $1 exd5 15. Nh4 $16) 14... Be4 {
Now Black is OK again.} (14... a4 $1 $132 {was very interesting.}) 15. Rfe1
Rab8 ({Black could also consider} 15... d5 {, for example:} 16. dxc5 bxc5 $1 (
16... Nxc5 {is also playable.} 17. cxd5 (17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxf6 gxf6 $11) 17...
Bxd5) 17. cxd5 exd5 {with a good game for Black.}) 16. h3 $2 ({Maybe White
should have considered} 16. a4 {, but this also has drawbacks.} d5) 16... h6 (
16... b5 $5) (16... cxd4 $5 17. Nxd4 e5 $132) 17. dxc5 Rxc5 $11 18. Bd4 $6 Rc6
19. Qd2 $2 e5 $17 20. Bb2 Nc5 (20... b5 $1 $19) 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 Na4 23.
Rc1 Rbc8 $19 24. Ba3 Rxc4 25. Rxc4 Rxc4 26. b5 Nc5 27. Rd1 d5 28. Qb2 d4 29.
Rc1 Rxc1+ 30. Qxc1 Nd5 31. Bxc5 bxc5 32. Qa3 Nc3 33. b6 Nxe2+ 34. Kf1 Nc3 35.
Qa7 Qe6 $2 (35... Qxa7 $1 36. bxa7 Nb5 37. Nxe5 Bxg2+ 38. Kxg2 Nxa7 $19) 36.
Nd2 Bxg2+ 37. Kxg2 Qc6+ 38. Kh2 Qb5 $4 39. Qa8+ 1-0

