1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. g3 b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O
O-O 9. Rd1 a6 {Interesting - Black thinks that d4-d5 is not a threat and
prepares counterplay with ...b5.} 10. a3 (10. d5 {was possible. Black can keep
the balance with} Bxc3 11. Qxc3 exd5 12. Nh4 d4 $1 {This is important - if
White had managed to play cxd5, he would have had a big advantage.} 13. Rxd4
Bxg2 14. Nxg2 Qe7 $11) 10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 b5 $5 12. c5 (12. b3 Be4) 12... Be4
{Now Black is ready to play ...Nd5 and ...f5.} 13. b4 ({After} 13. Bg5 h6 14.
Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Rac1 Nd5 16. Qd2 a5 {Black has good play.} (16... f5 {can also
be considered.})) 13... Nd5 14. Qb3 h6 (14... f5 $2 {runs into} 15. Ng5 $1 $18)
15. Bb2 f5 16. Nd2 $2 {After exchanging the light-squared bishop White's king
is quite weak.} (16. Bf1 f4 $1 ({Giving up the bishop is not justified here:} 
16... Bxf3 $6 17. Qxf3 f4 18. Bc1 $1 fxg3 19. Qxg3 $16) 17. Nd2 Bg6 $132) (16.
Bh3 $5 $13) 16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Qe8 $17 18. e3 Qh5 19. Qd3 f4 20. e4 fxg3 21.
fxg3 Rf2+ $1 $19 22. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 23. Ke1 Rf8 24. Nf3 Qxg3+ 0-1

