1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 {This was very
popular in the past, but it has been superseded by other continuations.} 7. g3
Bb7 8. Nf3 (8. f3 $2 {is strongly met with either} d5 $1 ({or} 8... c5 $1) 9.
Bg2 c5 {Black can afford to sacrifice a pawn since White is far behind in
development.} (9... dxc4 $5) 10. dxc5 Nbd7 11. cxb6 Rc8 $17) 8... d6 (8... a5 {
was an alternative. White should not play} 9. b4 $2 {as the opening of the
position clearly favours Black, who is ahead in development. For example} (9.
b3 $142 Be4 $11) 9... axb4 10. axb4 Ne4 11. Qb2 Rxa1 12. Qxa1 Nc6 13. Qb2 Nd6
$5 14. c5 Nc4 15. Qc3 b5 $17) (8... d5 $5 {also makes perfect sense.} 9. Bg2
dxc4 10. Qxc4 Nbd7 11. O-O c5 12. Rd1 Bd5 $1 13. Qd3 c4 $132 {Black has
excellent chances. He controls the centre and has a mobil majority on the
queenside.}) 9. Bg2 a5 10. b3 Nbd7 11. O-O Qe7 (11... Be4 {is another typical
move. For example} 12. Bb2 Qb8 $5 {Black prepares ...b5. This is especially
good if White has played a3 and b3.} 13. Rac1 b5 14. cxb5 Qxb5 $15) 12. Bb2 Be4
$11 13. Rfd1 h6 14. Rac1 Rfe8 15. Ne1 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 e5 17. Ne3 e4 18. b4 (18.
c5 $5) 18... Qe6 19. Kg2 axb4 20. axb4 d5 21. cxd5 $2 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Qxd5 23.
Qxc7 Nf6 24. Qc2 h5 25. h4 Red8 26. Kg1 e3 27. Rd3 $4 (27. f3 Qd6 28. Kg2 Qxb4
$15) 27... exf2+ 28. Kxf2 Re8 $19 29. Rf3 Qe6 30. Qc4 Qh3 31. Kg1 Rac8 32. Qd3
