1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 {Against this move order, Black
cannot play an early ...b6.} d6 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Nbd7 8. O-O Rb8 9. Qa4 {
An interesting move, provoking ...a6, which Black wouldn't like to play.} a6
10. Qc2 b6 11. e4 Bb7 {White has some advantage and he can continue in several
ways.} 12. Nh4 (12. Re1 {preparing the manoeuvre Nd2-f1-e3, was also
interesting.} Re8 13. Nd2) 12... Re8 13. f4 e5 {Now, White has to decide how
to deal with the tension in the centre. White found a remarkable idea:} 14.
fxe5 $1 dxe5 15. d5 $1 $16 {Even though Black has no a seemingly great outpost
on c5, his position is somewhat worse!} Qe7 (15... Nc5 $2 16. Bg5) 16. Qe2 b5
17. Be3 bxc4 18. Nf5 Qa3 19. g4 $1 Nc5 20. Nxg7 $1 Kxg7 21. Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 22.
Qf2+ Kg7 (22... Ke7 23. Bxc5+ $18) 23. Bh6+ $1 {A fantastic attacking game by
the player with the white pieces!} 1-0

