1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3
Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qc7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. a4 Re8 12. Ba3 c4 13. Bc2 {White to move,
would continue with Nd2, slowly preparing the advance f3-e4.} Bg4 14. Qe1 $5 {
White unpins the knight while keeping the pawns on c3 and e3 protected.} Bh5 {
Black prepares the exchange of bishops with ...Bg6.} ({After} 14... Bxf3 15.
gxf3 {White will continue with Kh1, Rg1, etc.}) 15. Nh4 $1 {This is stronger
than Nd2. If Black plays ...Bg6, White will take it with the knight.} (15. Nd2
Bg6 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. f3 Qa5 $15) 15... Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. f3 $1 $16 {
This is the right plan - Black has no satisfactory answer to this.} Nh5 18. Qf2
Qa5 19. Qd2 Rad8 20. Rab1 ({It is too early for} 20. e4 $2 {due to} dxe4 21.
fxe4 Nxd4 $1 $19) 20... Rd7 21. Rb5 Qd8 22. e4 $1 {Finally White managed to
push e4 and his advantage will increase.} a6 23. Rbb1 dxe4 24. fxe4 Nf6 25. Qf4
$18 {With a strong pair of bishops and a mobile pawn centre White has a
winning advantage.} Qa5 26. Qf3 b5 27. e5 Nd5 28. Be4 Nxe5 29. dxe5 Rxe5 30.
Rbd1 Qd8 31. Bxd5 Rexd5 32. Rxd5 Rxd5 33. Qxf7+ Kh7 34. axb5 axb5 35. Bf8 Rd7
36. Qf3 Rd3 37. Qb7 Rd7 38. Qxb5 Rd1 39. Qxc4 Qb6+ 40. Bc5 Rxf1+ 41. Kxf1 Qb1+
1-0

