1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 (6... Ne4 7.
Qc2 f5 8. Nh3 $1 {White prepares f3 and he keeps a slight advantage due to his
pair of bishops.} (8. f3 $2 Qh4+) 8... d6 9. f3 Nf6 10. e3 e5 11. dxe5 dxe5 12.
Nf2 $14) 7. Bg5 Bb7 8. e3 d6 9. Ne2 Nbd7 10. Qd3 {White prepares to develop
with Nc3, etc.} Ba6 11. Nc3 d5 12. Qc2 dxc4 13. Qa4 Bb7 14. Qxc4 c5 15. Rd1 {
White delays the development of the kingside. His hopes are based on the
long-term advantage of the pair of bishops.} h6 16. Bh4 Rc8 17. f3 {Blocking
the bishop on b7 and finally preparing the development of the f1-bishop.} a6
18. dxc5 Rxc5 19. Qd4 Qc7 20. e4 b5 21. Be2 Rc6 22. O-O $16 {White finally
completed his development. Since Black was not able to create any special
counterplay, White enjoys some advantage due to his pair of bishops.} Qb6 {
From Black's point of view, I would prefer to keep the queens on the board to
keep the position more complicated.} 23. Bf2 Qxd4 24. Rxd4 e5 25. Rb4 Rc7 (
25... Nb6 26. a4 $1 $18) 26. a4 $1 {White opens the position on the queenside
which increases his advantage.} bxa4 27. Ra1 Rb8 28. Raxa4 Bc8 29. Rxb8 Nxb8
30. Rc4 Rxc4 31. Bxc4 {The minor piece ending is clearly better for White - he
managed to convert his advantage.} Bb7 32. Na4 Nbd7 33. Nc5 Nxc5 34. Bxc5 Nd7
35. Bd6 g6 36. Kf2 Kg7 37. Ke3 f6 38. g3 Nb6 39. Be6 Bc8 40. Bxc8 Nxc8 41. Bc5
Kf7 42. Kd3 Ke6 43. Kc4 f5 44. Kb4 Kd7 45. Ka5 Kc6 46. b4 Kb7 47. h3 1-0

