1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b5 7. cxb5 c6 {
An interesting gambit. However, White can soon return the pawn and keep a
small advantage.} 8. Bg5 $5 cxb5 9. e3 Bb7 10. Nf3 {By returning the pawn,
White has a small, risk-free advantage.} a6 11. Bd3 d6 (11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 d5
13. Rg1 $16 (13. O-O $5 Nbd7 14. Kh1)) 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Rfc1 {I like this
decision. White keeps a rook on a1 since a3-a4 may be played at some point.}
Qb6 (13... Rc8 14. Qb3 $14) 14. Qc7 Rfc8 15. Qxb6 Nxb6 16. Nd2 {This is one of
my favourite types of positions: White has the pair of bishops in an endgame
with a symmetrical pawn structure.} Kf8 (16... d5 {How should White continue
now?} 17. Bxf6 {First, we eliminate one knight,} (17. Nb3 $132 Ne4) (17. f3 Nc4
$132) 17... gxf6 {and now we play} 18. Nb3 {with a classic advantage for White.
} Nc4 19. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yb3c5,Yb2b3]}) 17. f3 h6 18. Bf4 $1 Ke7 19.
e4 $1 $16 Rxc1+ 20. Rxc1 Rc8 21. Rxc8 {If it were possible, it would be
preferable to keep the rooks on the board. However, in this case, this would
give some counterchances to Black.} Bxc8 22. b3 Nfd7 23. Be3 d5 24. e5 {
Closing the position for now, but also gaining a serious space advantage.} Nb8
25. f4 Nc6 {White has the perfect setup on the queenside, restricting both of
Black's knights. He can expand on the kingside to increase his advantage.} 26.
g4 f5 {What should White play now?} 27. exf6+ $1 {The position is opened up
again.} Kxf6 {After this, White gets the e5-square for his knight. He managed
to convert his advantage.} (27... gxf6 28. Nf3 {Here, White can push g5 at
some point, creating an outside passed pawn.}) 28. Nf3 Bd7 29. Ne5 Be8 30. Bd2
Nc8 31. Nxc6 Bxc6 32. Bb4 Be8 33. h4 $2 Bg6 34. Bxg6 Kxg6 35. h5+ Kf7 36. Bc5
Ne7 $2 {The decisive mistake - the pawn ending is winning for White.} ({
Black could have defended with} 36... g6 37. hxg6+ Kxg6 38. Kg2 h5 39. g5 a5
40. a4 b4 41. Kg3 Kh7 42. Kh3 Kg7 43. Kh2 Kh7 44. Kg3 Kg7 45. Kh4 Kg6 $11) 37.
Bxe7 $1 $18 Kxe7 38. Kf2 Kf6 39. Kg3 Kf7 40. b4 Ke7 41. g5 Kf7 42. Kg4 Ke7 43.
f5 1-0

