1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 7. Bg5 Bb7 8.
f3 h6 9. Bh4 d5 10. e3 Nbd7 11. cxd5 {This used to be one of the main lines in
the Nimzo.} Nxd5 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. Be7 Rfe8 14. Bh4 Nd5 15. Bf2 {Again, White
has the pair of bishops in the endgame. As compensation, Black has some
activity.} e5 (15... c5 {can be considered. For example} 16. e4 N5f6 17. Ne2
$14) 16. e4 exd4 17. O-O-O Nf4 18. Bxd4 {White is enjoying a nice advantage. A
typical method to fight against the pair of bishops is to create strong
squares for one's pieces. Here, Black cannot create any outposts. The
asymmetric pawn structure in this position favours the side with the pair of
bishops.} Ne5 19. Be3 Ne6 20. Ne2 Rad8 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 c5 23. Bc3 Rxd1+
24. Kxd1 Bc6 25. Kc2 Ng6 26. Ba6 Rd8 (26... Kf8 27. Rd1 Nh4 28. Bf1 $16) 27. b3
Nh4 28. Re1 $5 {Such small tactics of two to three moves are very important in
the endgame!} b5 (28... f6 29. Bf1 $16) 29. Re2 $16 {White has defended the
g2-pawn in a comfortable way, and he is ready to expel the knight with Be1.
Kociscak managed to convert his advantage against the future Super-GM.} Ng6 30.
Rd2 Rxd2+ 31. Kxd2 Nh4 32. Be5 Nxg2 33. Bb8 f5 34. Bxa7 fxe4 35. fxe4 g5 36.
Bxc5 h5 37. Kc3 Ne1 38. Bd6 g4 39. Kd4 Bd7 40. Kc5 Nd3+ 41. Kb6 Kf7 42. Bxb5
Bxb5 43. Kxb5 h4 44. Kc4 Ne1 45. Kd5 Ke8 46. a4 Kd8 47. a5 Kc8 48. a6 Nf3 49.
b4 1-0

