{A true masterpiece by Spanish GM Vallejo Pons!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Qxc3 d6 7. d4 b6 8. g3 Bb7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O c5 (
10... a5 11. b3 Be4 {is the other typical plan for Black.}) 11. Rd1 Qe7 12. b4
{Black has played reasonably until now, but here he commits a serious mistake:}
d5 $2 {It was better to keep the tension.} (12... Rfc8 $5) (12... Rac8 $5) 13.
bxc5 bxc5 14. Qb2 Nb6 15. cxd5 Bxd5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 $14 {As a result of 12...d5,
the position has opened up which favours the pair of bishops.} 17. Be3 Qe7 18.
Qb4 $1 {White exchanges into a favourable endgame.} Qxb4 19. axb4 Rfc8 20. Bf1
$1 {White wants to activated the knight on f3 without exchanging the
light-squared bishops.} Ne4 ({After} 20... Bxf3 21. exf3 Nfd5 22. Bc5 $16 {
Black has one good knight on d5, but his other pieces are passive.}) 21. Ne5
Nc4 {I don't like this - exchanging one pair of knights does not help Black.}
22. Bd4 Nxe5 23. Bxe5 Rc2 24. Rdc1 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 f6 26. Bf4 g5 27. Be3 a5 28.
f3 Nd6 29. Bc5 Nf7 30. e4 Bb7 31. Bc4 axb4 32. Bxe6 {White will pick up the
pawn on b4 with some winning chances.} Re8 33. Bb3 Rc8 34. Rc2 Kg7 35. Bxb4 Ne5
36. Rxc8 Bxc8 37. Kg2 Ba6 38. Bc3 Kg6 39. Kf2 Bc4 40. Ba4 Kf7 41. Bd1 Ba6 42.
f4 gxf4 43. gxf4 {In order to make progress White had to play f4. Next, he
will activate his king.} Nd7 44. Ke3 Bc4 45. Kd4 Ba2 46. Bh5+ Kg7 47. Be8 Nf8
48. f5 $1 $18 {Now, Black's knight will be permanently boxed in - White is
winning.} h6 49. Kc5 Bb1 50. Bc6 Nh7 51. h4 $1 Bd3 52. Kd6 Be2 53. Ba4 Kf8 54.
Bb3 Bf3 55. Bc2 Kf7 56. Bd2 h5 57. Bh6 Nf8 58. Bb3+ Ke8 59. Bd5 Nh7 60. Bg7 Be2
61. Bg8 1-0

