1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 c5 7. O-O dxc4 8. Bxc4
cxd4 (8... a6 {is a little-known but interesting continuation.}) (8... Nc6 {
is one of the main lines.}) 9. exd4 Nbd7 10. Bg5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qc7 12. Bd3 $5
b6 {Black prefers to keep developing over winning the pawn on c3 which could
be quite risky.} 13. Rc1 Bb7 14. Re1 $1 (14. Qe2 {may look very logical but it
is a mistake.} Ng4 $1 {This forces a concession. Either White must weaken his
king with g3, or he must exchange the light-squared bishops.} 15. Be4 (15. g3
$6 $15 Qc6) 15... Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Ngf6 17. Qe2 Rac8 18. c4 {Black is on the
better side of equality in this position.}) 14... Rfe8 (14... Ng4 $2 {is not
effective after Re1 and it is simply met with} 15. h3 $1 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qh2+ 17.
Kf1 $16) 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 (16. Rxe5 $1) 16... Qc6 17. f3 Nd7 {Black is
doing well.} 18. Qe2 {Now Black went for an interesting operation:} Qc5+ 19.
Kh1 Qxe5 $1 20. Qxe5 Nxe5 21. Rxe5 f6 $15 {The resulting endgame is more
pleasant for Black.} 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Bc4 fxg5 24. Bxe6+ Kf8 25. Kg1 Rd8 26.
Bb3 Rc8 27. Kf2 Rc5 28. Kg3 b5 29. Rd1 Bc8 30. Rd8+ Ke7 31. Rh8 Rxc3 32. Rxh7
Kf6 33. Rh8 a5 34. Rf8+ Ke5 35. Re8+ Kd6 36. Rg8 a4 37. Bf7 Rc7 38. Bg6 b4 39.
Rd8+ Ke5 40. Be4 Rc5 41. Rg8 Be6 42. Rb8 Bxa2 43. Rxb4 Ra5 44. Bc2 a3 45. h4
gxh4+ 46. Rxh4 Ra7 47. Re4+ Kd5 48. Re8 Kd4 49. Be4 Bb3 50. Bb1 Kc3 51. Re2 Rd7
52. Bf5 Rd2 53. Re3+ Kb2 54. Be6 Bxe6 55. Rxe6 a2 56. Rb6+ Kc1 57. Ra6 Kb1 0-1

