{This was only blitz game, yet it still is quite instructive!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 c5 5. d5 h6 6. Bh4 d6 7. e3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 e5 9. e4 g6 {
This was a mouse slip ... Black wanted to play ...g5 and did so on the next
move.} 10. Bd3 g5 11. Bg3 Nbd7 12. h3 ({After} 12. h4 {Black is prepared to
give up the h-file since White cannot easily exploit this.} Rg8 13. hxg5 hxg5)
12... Nf8 13. Nf3 Ng6 $17 {Black is in full control.} 14. O-O Kd7 $1 {This is
not a mouse slip :-) I like this manoeuvre! The king will be perfectly safe on
c7.} 15. Qa4+ Kc7 16. Qa5+ b6 17. Qb5 Qe8 18. Qb3 Bd7 19. a4 a5 $1 {Black
stops any counterplay. White will not be able to exploit the backward pawn on
b6.} 20. Qc2 Rb8 21. Rab1 (21. Nd4 {This is a typical move in these structures.
Here, it is not good and Black can even ignore it!} Nf4 $1 (21... cxd4 {
would offer some chances to White.} 22. cxd4 exd4 $2 23. c5 $1 $18) 22. Nb5+
Bxb5 $19) 21... Nh5 22. Bh2 Nhf4 $19 {Later, Black managed to open files on
the kingside and win convincingly.} 23. Rb2 Bxa4 24. Qb1 Rg8 25. Bxf4 Nxf4 26.
Bc2 Bd7 27. Qa2 g4 28. Nh4 gxh3 29. Nf5 Bxf5 30. Kh2 Rxg2+ 31. Kh1 Bg4 32. Rg1
Bf3 33. Rxg2 hxg2+ 34. Kg1 Ne2+ {Zeit (Lag: Av=0.23s, max=0.5s) .} 0-1

